            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Hello there. I thought I'd add to this conversation. At least at the surface, I seem to be experiencing the same issue as described here, but in a different manner. \n\nI usually launch Neovim by doing `Ctrl+L` in Explorer and writing `nvim <relativefilename>`. When resizing a NeoVim window, everything works perfectly fine, but if I maximize the NVim window and then minimize it, weird things start to happen.\n\nFirst, the interface looks very weird:\n<img width=\"960\" height=\"492\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/9dca6198-90d0-4b5b-86c1-bad3ef69d1c5\" />\n\n<details><summary>(here how it's supposed to look if you're wondering for some reason)</summary>\n<p>\n\n<img width=\"959\" height=\"462\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/42924280-7818-4fc2-b2b6-4ae73d4e2595\" />\n\n</p>\n</details> \n\nBut if I try resizing the window in any way after that (including maximizing), then these ugly scrollbars appear and they're the worst. Sometimes the horizontal bar blocks the command line completely unless you fiddle around with the size.\n<img width=\"1017\" height=\"519\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/d1839530-c994-4b6f-b5c8-4a261f391eb6\" />\n\nI like working with Vim while maximized/fullscreen and you're always one mistype/misclick away from having to completely restart Vim, so I've been desperately trying to find a solution, which is how I've found this issue. I know it's a very old one, but the issue is still present on the latest stable release. I'll be more than happy to help.\n\nI'm open to answering any other questions, but for starters some of my specs are:\n```\nWindows 10 - 1909 (Build 18363.657)\nStandard Windows Command Prompt [Version 10.0.18363.657]\nJust incase, installed the freshest stable NVim release off of the official source, issue persists\n```\n\nI think there are some useful directions I could take this, I have access to a bunch of different computers I could test this on with interesting spec variations, though I'm not able to do it all today. I'm open to whatever communications and have subscribed to the issue.",
