            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "@crwebb85 Okay, I did some experimenting and found something very interesting out. For starters, I'll respond to Your most recent comment.\n\n### Response\n\nNo, `Ctrl + L` doesn't open any terminal; otherwise, I would've mentioned it. Yes, it opens the \"filepath bar\", but that's the whole point: it's not just some bloatware bar for full filepaths. You could think of it like a mini-command bar. You could do `ping example.com`; `cmd`, which opens the command prompt in the directory You're at in Explorer; You could navigate directories by typing their names, open files and binaries and etc. ...\n\nI don't know, maybe it's just a power user thing, but for a clear example, say there's this filetree:\n- files\n  - code\n    - main.c\n\nI could navigate to `files\\` (either by mouse, keyboard or the aforementioned command line), and do `nvim code\\main.c` in the command line to open `main.c` in Vim with root `files\\`. It'll open a command prompt terminal delegated by Windows specifically for Vim. And there comes in the catch I found out.\n\n### Findings\n\nThrough some experimentation, I may have just found out how to replicate this issue.\n\nSay, You've got a `cmd` window, already open, right? That's the usual way I see everybody here uses Vim. If You open NVim by doing `nvim` there, it works perfectly fine! The problem actually goes away!\n\n<img width=\"618\" height=\"200\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/7cf75878-236e-4cb3-90ef-3f4a14ff4274\" />\n\n<img width=\"318\" height=\"327\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/054a7d58-360d-47f9-93a9-48d30273168d\" />\n<img width=\"480\" height=\"248\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/7f81f354-1de1-4715-a327-706c2143a8a4\" />\n\nBut, when I work, this is super inconvenient for a thousand and one reason. So instead, I open NVim with the \"Run\" menu (`Super + R` if someone doesn't know that either somehow) or with the Explorer command line again. As said in the reply, that will open a terminal delegated specifically for Vim (which is one of the reasons), You can tell because an NVim instance launched from `cmd` will retain the `cmd` logo and group in with any other command prompts you may have open, while a separate NVim window will get its icon and will have a separate group for NVim instances:\n\n<img width=\"161\" height=\"163\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a491c9fe-4e1e-4ef8-ba23-73bba900eb2c\" />\n\nWell, here's the thing, for some reason, the \"cool\" NVim, that was lauched independently, is the one that has this bug! So here's the theorem:\n_Launching NVim independently highlights the problem, while launching with a terminal already as a parent omits it._\n\nWhat I want right now is for some of You to test out, whether the problem appears if you launch NVim using these steps:\n1. Press `Windows + R`\n2. Type `nvim`\nThis should open NVim independently. If the issue can be replicated on Your machines, great! If not, the bug is a bit more sophisticated, but I still have ideas. I'll be ready to hear back from You.\n\nSome guesses as to what's happening is that when NVim \"creates\" its own window, it may come with unfavourable settings, that are otherwise set in instantiated terminals, but I'm not sure. Opening other terminal programs \"independently\" does not seem to replicate the same bug.\n\n### ==============================================================\n\nAnyways, hope You're having an awesome day, nice to see some progress. Peace!",
